[normal]Why Inclusion is the way to go for governments[bold],[bold] and donor aid should target this[bold]For the period  2009 – 2012, ANCEFA
[normal],
[normal] with the support of Save the Children UK, undertook an action-oriented survey in the E
[normal]conomic 
[normal]C
[normal]ommunity 
[normal]O
[normal]f 
[normal]W
[normal]est 
[normal]A
[normal]frican 
[normal]S
[normal]tates (ECOWAS)
[normal] region of Africa to underscore the significance of  inclusive 
[normal]e
[normal]ducation
[normal],
[normal] and how it would accelerate  access to quality 
[normal]e
[normal]ducation by children with disabilities. 
[normal]Many children
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]of 
[normal]whom most are psychologically or physically disabled
[normal],
[normal] are prevented from going to school simply because no one thought about integrating adapted learning, teaching and construction facilities to accommodate them. 
[normal]Not less that 5% of the total children population in the countries of the region have been projected to have one disability or another (ANCEFA Report ECOWAS, 2013)
[normal]The first shocking revelation is that there is absolutely no reliable 
[normal]disaggregated 
[normal]data 
[normal] showing
[normal]  statistics 
[normal]on the number 
[normal]of  disabled children, 
[normal]less 
[normal] 
[normal]still 
[normal]on the nature of 
[normal]their 
[normal]disability. ANCEFA and partners thus heavily rooted for an inclusive 
[normal]e
[normal]ducation process that would ensure that EVERY child is in school
[normal],
[normal] and LEARNING. Development partners have thus been called upon to support the process
[normal],
[normal] with governments being asked to take the lead
[normal],
[normal] since delivery of 
[normal]inclusive education 
[normal] should be the top priority of every government
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Further, disabled children and girls in rural areas do not go to school and in urban areas, special schools are insufficient. Consequently, most disabled children are totally excluded from the educational system.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Inclusive 
[normal]e
[normal]ducation relates to all children accessing and meaningfully participating in quality 
[normal]e
[normal]ducation in ways that are responsive to their individual needs. Inclusive education is therefore expected to meet EVERYONE’s rights to Education.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is universally agreed that every child has a fundamental right to 
[normal]e
[normal]ducation
[normal] and that every child CAN Learn. Further every stakeholder
[normal],
[normal] and 
[normal]every 
[normal]lead agenc
[normal]y, 
[normal] including governments and donor aid agencies
[normal],
[normal] should acknowledge and respect differences in children. Education structures, systems and methodologies must meet the needs of 
[normal]all 
[normal] children, and where historically disabled children have been discriminated against, schools have to accommodate children with special educational needs and redress the past imbalance
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Increasing awareness and vigilance among communities, enhancing capacity building of MPs and journalists on inclusive education, budget tracking and child rights, advocacy on inclusive education and increased budget allocations, popularization of instruments and texts on children
[normal]s’
[normal] rights, 
[normal]and 
[normal]sensitization and lobbying using diverse means should help address the problem
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]National and international partnerships need to be enhanced to tackle the perennial exclusion of the children with disability from education. A call to all international aid agencies to promote this would be a welcome move.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]12 December 2013
